{
  "texts": [
    "If G is a split semisimple Lie group that is not necessarily adjoint type, we abuse terminology by saying ρ ∈ Hom(π 1 (B), G) lies in a Hitchin component if the conjugacy class of Ad •ρ does.",
    "Hitchin components are homeomorphic to open balls of dimension (2g -2) dim G, where g is the genus of B.",
    "Since the underlying manifold M n+2 = B × ρ N remains constant when ρ varies in a fixed component, Theorem B yields the existence of a (2g -2)(n 2 -1)-parameter family of complete expanding Ricci solitons on M n+2 admitting a free, local, isometric R n -action.If we fix a conformal structure c on the closed surface B 2, we are able to exhibit more solutions to the twisted harmonic-Einstein equations by exploiting the non-abelian Hodge correspondence:Theorem C. Let c be a conformal class on a closed surface B 2 of genus at least 2.",
    "Then, there is a oneto-one correspondence between equivalence classes of solutions (g B, ρ, h) to the twisted harmonic-Einstein equations (4) with g B ∈ c, and equivalence classes of polystable G-Higgs bundles (P, Φ) over (B, c) with tr Φ 2 = 0 up to pullback by automorphisms of (B 2, c).Higgs bundles were introduced by Hitchin [Hit87] and Simpson [Sim88], and have been extensively studied since then.",
    "We refer the reader to Section 4 below for their definition and related notions such as stability and equivalence."
  ]
}